# Collective intelligence for the analysis of emerging signals 

## Image: What does it look like?


![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Reference: Where can we find more information or download materials?


<a href="Exploración Template (mural.co)" target=" blank">Exploración Template (mural.co)</a>

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



This is a template useful for conducting collective intelligence exercises centered in analyzing early signals of change. It can be used with your team, stakeholders, and other participants. The template includes three main sections: an initial ice-breaking space, a section for analyzing the relationship between the signals and the Sustainable Development Goals (SGDs), and a final segment for assessing the relevance of the signals for the future of your country (configured here for Argentina). You can adapt this template to your own country and context.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



This template can help you to enhance your prospective analysis in your R&amp;D practice. By using collective intelligence for building prospective knowledge and evidence, you will be able to gather more diverse information and points of views. Furthermore, it can help you to set in motion mechanisms to better listen to voices that are often overlooked. Moreover, you will be able to better recollect local knowledge in your prospective analysis.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)



A template useful for conducting collective intelligence exercises centered in analyzing early signals of change.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?



The template starts with an opening section in which participants are asked to introduce themself and to indicate their favorite pastime. This first task is designed to help participants to loosen up and to get familiar with the digital platform used for this template, which is Mural. After this, the general description of the exercise dynamic is given to the participants.  
  
The next section offers a space for analyzing the relationship between signals of change and the SGDs. The signals displayed are the result of an exploration we conducted for identifying and analyzing which signals of change could have a significant impact in Argentina’s development over the next 10 years. You can adapt this template to display the signals that are important for your country or team.  
  
In the last section, participants can assign a relevance score to each signal. The score goes from 1 to 5, 5 being the most relevant and 1 the least.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)



To implement this tool, it is helpful to have collaborators willing to act as facilitators for the exercise. Depending on the number of participants you want to involve, you may need to plan for one or more facilitators.  
  
This is a template made in Mural, so it is most useful when conducting online exercises. If you are working with a team, or participants, lacking the technical requirements (or skills) for a smooth collaborative online session, you will need to think about adapting this template to use it in an offline manner.

## Reflections: What to keep in mind when using the tool for R&amp;D purposes?



This template is most useful when you have a genuine interest in adding diversity and inclusivity to your R&amp;D practice, particularly your future-looking practice. When in your team, or organization, there is little interest in both future perspectives and collective intelligence, it may not be the best moment for using this tool.

# Collective Intelligence to recover local knowledge 

## Image: What does it look like?


## Reference: Where can we find more information or download materials?


Moscovich L., Gete M., Moreno M.V.(2024). Fertilizacion Cruzada de Saberes Locales. La experiencia del taller nativa: flora de concepción. Programa de las Naciones Unidas para el Desarrollo. (not published yet)

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



This methodology uses collective intelligence to recover and integrate diverse local knowledge from different stakeholders to use it to take action for SDGs. Collective intelligence activities, implemented by Co Lab, the Accelerator Lab of UNDP Argentina, are used for different purposes: holding meetings, projects, workshops and experiments. Collective intelligence activities leverage the diverse knowledge and experiences of all participants, facilitating a dialogue that is both free and structured. This dialogue is free in the sense that all ideas, voices, and opinions are promoted. On the other hand, dialogue is structured because it has specific predefined goals that it seeks to achieve.  
  
In 2023, within the climate action learning cycle, Co Lab facilitated a workshop with various instances of collective intelligence for the exchange of knowledge with the objective of retrieving information about a given topic. At the same time, we were working on resilience against the effects of climate change. We organize a workshop to raise awareness about the native flora and its role in the environment. The workshop gathered NGOs, research centers, universities, residents, plant nurseries, park rangers, and lifeguards. Discussions revolved around different circumstances, obstacles, and possibilities in relation to native flora and led to the formulation of action plans to promote its adoption.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



We use this methodology for R&amp;D because it enables the recovery and utilization of different kinds of knowledge and also understanding of specific needs and challenges faced by different stakeholders. In this case local knowledge results essential for understanding and addressing complex issues, especially in the context of climate change and environmental sustainability. By incorporating a diversity of perspectives and experiences, collective intelligence enriches the available data, providing a broader and deeper knowledge base that can lead to more effective and tailored innovations.  
  
For instance, in projects related to climate change adaptation, collective intelligence can uncover and systematize local knowledge about natural resource management practices, resilience to extreme weather phenomena, and the use of native species that are crucial for the development of effective technologies and intervention strategies. When this type of knowledge is integrated into the design and planning phases of R&amp;D, it ensures that the solutions are not only technically feasible but also socially acceptable and aligned with local cultural and ecological practices. This is crucial for ensuring the sustainability and long-term success of R&amp;D initiatives.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)



It is an innovative methodology that utilizes collective intelligence activities to recover and use local knowledge, harnessing a group's diverse experiences and information.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?



In our case, we use this methodology to organize a workshop on native flora but can be extrapolated to other topics. The steps we followed were the following:  
  
Identify local key collaborators who are linked in some way to the topic in question. In our case these collaborators were local organizations, universities, nurseries, museums, park rangers, kayakers, lifeguards, and INTA.  
  
Define clear goals. In this step, it is essential first to set the big goals and then decompose them into smaller and more concrete goals. In the workshop our goals were recovering and sharing knowledge about native flora and raising awareness among the population about its importance for the local ecosystem.  
  
Select collective intelligence activities that allow you to achieve those goals from this menu. These activities must promote active participation from all attendees to recover local knowledge and foster exchanges of ideas. We selected a memory game (memotest) and DOOP Matrix (desires, opportunities, obstacles, plans).  
  
Prepare all necessary materials. Some activities require more preparation, for others a sheet of paper and a pencil are enough. In our case we use samples of native plants, forms for identifying species, cards designed by ourselves for the memory game, and materials for the DOOP Matrix.  
  
Conclude by summarizing the learnings, discussing potential follow-up actions based on the proposals that emerged, and documenting the results for future reference.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)



To effectively utilize this methodology for R&amp;D, it is essential to integrate several key elements:  
  
- It requires skills and technical expertise in the topic to be addressed. In the context of the native flora workshop, this includes environment and urbanism specialists, in addition to the UNDP team.  
  
- Specific conditions must be met, such as fostering a supportive environment that encourages active participation of everyone involved.  
  
- Various materials are necessary to carry out the activities; this will depend on the specific activities carried out. They may require only a pencil and paper or, as in our case, posters, prints, cards, and plant samples, among others.  
  
- Sufficient resources are needed, encompassing funding for logistics and materials, knowledgeable facilitators, and engaged community members. Although monetary resources are required, this methodology's main feature is that it can be deployed at different scales and budgets.

## Reflections: What to keep in mind when using the tool for R&amp;D purposes?



This methodology is useful in projects or interventions that focus on recovering local knowledge and involve diverse participants with different origins or experiences since they have specific information about the topic in the place involved. It is essential to create an environment where everyone feels free to participate in activities. It is advisable to break the ice with simpler questions, for example, having each participant introduce themselves and tell something they like. Adaptability is necessary to refine activities based on participant feedback and emerging findings. Since we cannot predict the level of knowledge of the participants, it is essential to be able to adapt accordingly. In the case of the workshop, although we had planned activities, we did not know the level of knowledge of the participants and, therefore, we had to be prepared to adapt the activities if necessary. Finally, it is important to create a space to share knowledge at the end of the activity and resolve doubts or confusion that may have arisen.

# Collective Intelligence for climate action

## Image: What does it look like?


## Reference: Where can we find more information or download materials?


<a href="https://www.undp.org/es/bolivia/blog/inteligencia-comunitaria-para-la-accion-climatica https://www.undp.org/es/bolivia/blog/horizontes-compartidos-integrando-sabidurias-indigenas-en-la-planificacion-nacional" target=" blank">https://www.undp.org/es/bolivia/blog/inteligencia-comunitaria-para-la-accion-climatica https://www.undp.org/es/bolivia/blog/horizontes-compartidos-integrando-sabidurias-indigenas-en-la-planificacion-nacional</a>

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



Bolivia uses collective intelligence for climate action, especially in adaptation planning with indigenous communities in areas such as the Amazon, Chiquitania and Chaco. The initiative sought to merge traditional and official knowledge by involving indigenous peoples in the development of “life systems plans” to address climate challenges and contribute to territorial development.  
  
In collaboration with the Kaami Indigenous Captaincy and the Municipality of Camiri, the UNDP Accelerator Lab engaged 16 indigenous communities to understand climate adaptation needs. Through workshops and a digital survey, community members prioritized climate issues, leading to the creation of a 3D climate adaptation map. This approach empowered indigenous groups in local planning and contributed their perspectives to national climate strategies.  
  
The Bolivian experience demonstrates the effectiveness of collective intelligence in empowering marginalized communities, fostering stakeholder dialogue and improving understanding of local ecosystems. Through the co-design of inclusive processes and the use of technology for data visualization, the initiative promoted meaningful participation and knowledge sharing, ultimately aiding informed decision-making and sustainable development in vulnerable regions of Bolivia.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



The utilization of collective intelligence methods and tools for Research and Development (R&amp;D) offers numerous benefits. Firstly, it brings together diverse perspectives, expertise, and insights from stakeholders, fostering innovative ideas and solutions. Collaborative processes encourage creativity and innovation, leading to novel approaches and breakthroughs. Moreover, collective intelligence streamlines problem-solving by leveraging collective knowledge, resulting in quicker identification of solutions and effective decision-making. Involving multiple stakeholders enhances engagement and ownership, fostering collaboration and shared responsibility for sustainable outcomes. Additionally, it provides a platform for validating ideas, receiving feedback, and refining concepts in real-time, ensuring solutions meet end-users' needs. Scalability and adaptability are facilitated by harnessing collective wisdom, allowing for broader implementation and greater impact.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)



Collective intelligence engages diverse communities to collaboratively address climate challenges, bridging knowledge gaps for sustainable development.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?



Collective intelligence is utilized in Research and Development (R&amp;D) by engaging diverse stakeholders to co-create innovative solutions, share knowledge, collaborate on problem-solving, and drive decision-making processes, leading to more effective and impactful outcomes in various fields of research and development.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)



Effectively utilizing collective intelligence for R&amp;D requires inclusive processes, meaningful community engagement, access to relevant technology and resources, facilitation of dialogue, and a commitment to integrating diverse perspectives into decision-making processes.

## Reflections: What to keep in mind when using the tool for R&amp;D purposes?



When using collective intelligence for R&amp;D purposes, it's essential to prioritize inclusivity, respect diverse perspectives, ensure meaningful community engagement, maintain transparency, foster trust, address power dynamics, leverage appropriate technology, facilitate effective communication, and commit to implementing outcomes that reflect the needs and priorities of all stakeholders involved.

## Image: What does it look like?

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



Collective intelligence is a form of shared knowledge and insights generated from the  
collaboration among stakeholders.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



Collective intelligence enables the mobilization of a wider range of information, ideas,  
and insights through the joint efforts of people. Collective intelligence can  
thus accelerate progress towards development goals by tapping into the  
brainpower of people and offers a solution for reaching agreements in uncertain  
times.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)



Collective intelligence is a sensemaking method for gathering insights through joint activities between  
stakeholders.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?



STEP 1: Define the  
challenge. Clarify the issue you are addressing and why it is important.  
  
STEP 2: Gather data,  
information and ideas. Explore uncommon sources of data and information that  
may portray the key challenge in a different light.  
  
STEP 3: Mobilize  
people. Carefully define and target participants, and consider their incentives  
and motivations for joining the collective intelligence exercise.  
  
STEP 4: Connect and  
Interpret. Design how people will contribute and interact in the collective  
intelligence activity. Think about how you will store and process data into  
results and insights.  
  
STEP 5: Prototype  
&amp; implement. Design how to turn results of collective intelligence into  
action. Create prototype and testing plan.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)



Collective intelligence requires a diverse group of contributors as diversity of people and perspectives enhances the collective intelligence of a group. Within this group, it is also essential  
to enable people to contribute their views and ideas independently and freely  
to avoid group biases. This method also works best with different sets of data  
to gather the most recent insights through real time data sources. It is also  
recommended to share the key insights and data collected from collective  
intelligence interventions to empower participants as actors of change and not  
passive beneficiaries.

# Collaborative design of actions. Collective intelligence for experimenting and scaling with others…

## Image: What does it look like?


## Reference: Where can we find more information or download materials?


Moscovich, L., Alzú, M. S., Gete, M., Sáenz Guillén, L. y Moreno, M. V. (2023). Collaborative design of actions. Collective intelligence for experimenting and scaling with others. Buenos Aires: UNDP. Available at: https://www.undp.org/es/argentina/publicaciones/collaborative-design-actions  

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



This toolkit explains the rationale and the step-by-step process to use the collaborative design approach. This approach builds on collective intelligence tools to design, implement, and scale interventions. It is also used for different purposes such as planning, team building, problem-solving, decision-making, innovation, and knowledge sharing. Collaborative design is an approach employed by the Co Lab, the Accelerator Lab of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in Argentina, to execute projects, such as workshops, experiments, and activities with different aims. This method is designed to engaging all participants, such as governments, leaders of the grassroots solutions being tested, relevant stakeholders, and different groups, in the design, development, and execution of interventions through collective intelligence tools that capitalize on their diverse knowledge and experiences. Furthermore, collective intelligence fosters structured and liberating dialogue simultaneously so that all voices can be heard. This approach is cost-effective, enhances coordination, and increases the legitimacy and adoption of actions. This guide details the step-by-step process, offering examples and resources to use it in different projects.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



The collaborative design of actions is cost-effective, enhances coordination, and increases the legitimacy and adoption of actions. The collaborative design involves numerous stakeholders coming from various disciplines and backgrounds. This diversity of perspectives can be challenging, but it also offers an opportunity, since a single problem can be seen, understood, defined, and addressed in different ways. The approach fosters activities where this plurality is expressed as participants are invited to and are put to work together by responding to different prompts. We used this approach for numerous projects, such as the PreserVamos initiative, where we worked jointly with the AppEAR team to develop an app, and with municipal governments where the initiative was carried out.  
  
This collaborative design approach is cost-effective because it requires relatively few monetary resources since it is based on cooperation and harnesses participants’ knowledge and skills through relatively simple activities. These activities can be facilitated at different scales and with different budgets. Still, collaborative design requires time and the active commitment of every stakeholder to keep meetings and conversations to plan every step together. As long as all the stakeholders express their opinions, needs, and points of view in these meetings, this approach enhances coordination and helps to align expectations, methods, and expected outcomes. Therefore, the final product arising from these activities –which could be an action, intervention or policy– is likely to be highly legitimate for all the participants, which in turn facilitates its adoption among all the stakeholders involved. This guide offers a step-by-step explanation, examples, and resources based on our experience, which will save time and money for those who want to implement it for the first time.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)



DIY! Use this collaborative design toolkit to design, experiment and scale innovations with others through collective intelligence activities.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?



The methodology proposed in this guide emphasizes the importance of collaboration in designing and implementing actions. The guide gives ideas and examples of collective intelligence and liberating structure activities and explains how to apply them step-by-step to foster the active participation of diverse stakeholders. These steps include:  
  
Selecting partners: Identifying strategic partners who can contribute diverse perspectives and expertise to the project.  
  
Forging bonds and building trust: Establishing a foundation of mutual understanding and trust among all project partners. This step requires investing time in constant communication through regular meetings and conversations.  
  
Defining the question: Articulating a clear, specific, and objective research question or hypothesis to guide the experiment. This question can be defined together, considering all stakeholders' goals.  
  
Formulating the hypothesis: Transitioning from a general hypothesis to specific hypotheses and considering different dimensions of analysis.  
  
Specific questions, variables, and indicators: Identifying specific research questions, variables to be measured, and appropriate indicators or proxies.  
  
Ideating the experimental design: Developing a detailed plan for the experiment, including the selection of dependent and independent variables, study population, and control and experimental groups.  
  
Taking action 1. Reverse engineering for planning: Planning the implementation of the solution, including defining stages, necessary materials, actors involved, and timeframes.  
  
Taking action 2. Distribute tasks: Assigning specific tasks to different partners, ensuring clarity in responsibilities and deadlines.  
  
Rethinking/visualizing the experiment: Engaging in speculative future exercises to envision the experiment's outcomes and identify any additional considerations.  
  
In summary, the methodology proposed in this guide emphasizes the importance of the collaborative design approach and provides ideas and examples to apply it. The ultimate goal is to design and implement effective and scalable solutions that address complex development challenges.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)



The first and most necessary requirement for this approach to succeed (and for this toolkit to be useful) is the participants' willingness, commitment, and agreement with the goals of the activity (pilot, workshop, experiment) being designed and with the collaborative design approach. This, of course, is an iterative process in which, many times, the goals and the methodologies of the activities are discussed; therefore, they are legitimate for the participants.. For instance, as the PreserVamos project demanded coordinated actions  with the AppEAR team and three local municipal governments, we organized regular meetings and a weekly schedule.. Each organization should have a leader or champion who can devote their time to the project and be available all along the process. Collaborative design is a time-intensive process that requires regular meetings, discussions, and coordination among all the partners involved. Also, while the Co Lab uses the approach to facilitate the activities through collective intelligence tools, experts in the fields being addressed are necessary as well. For instance, in the case of the native plants project in Concepción del Uruguay, in the province of Entre Ríos, in Argentina, which we carried out with this approach, we had a team comprised of environment and urbanism specialists, in addition to the UNDP team. A diverse team with expertise in relevant fields is crucial for generating innovative solutions. Engaging stakeholders throughout the process ensures inclusivity and alignment with the target audience's needs. Monetary resources are also needed, but this approach's main feature is that it can be deployed at different scales and budgets. Engagement is the clue to success.

## Reflections: What to keep in mind when using the tool for R&amp;D purposes?



This tool is useful in projects or interventions involving diverse stakeholders with different backgrounds or experiences. This approach is beneficial when working with local partners who have information about the place or community involved. It is important to be aware of potential challenges such as communication difficulties and stakeholders’ engagement. It is fundamental to generate a space of communication, select a leader to track each activity (it can be a leader for the entire project or a leader for each activity) and be patient since coordination can be demanding  in the process.

# Collective Intelligence

## Image: What does it look like?

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Reference: Where can we find more information or download materials?

<a href="https://www.undp.org/acceleratorlabs/collective-intelligence-sustainable-development-getting-smarter-together" target=" blank">https://www.undp.org/acceleratorlabs/collective-intelligence-sustainable-development-getting-smarter-together</a>

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)

Collective Intelligence for Sustainable Development

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)

Our Lab used Collective Intelligence for the purpose of bringing extensive understanding and working with solid waste management complex system and therefore map informal urban infrastructure in the process of improving solid waste management system. The process combined both citizens generated data, crowd mapping using satellite data to respond SDG 11. It proved to be an effective method as within a span of 3 weeks over 26,000 features were mapped including roads, waterways, buildings and trash sites. It identified areas covered with waste collection system and uncovered areas, very useful attribute information visualization of overall waste management situation to inform decision making.
